__de__ What I also realized at that point was that it was not only Cambodia , but of the 113 developing countries that torture , 93 of these countries have all passed laws that say you have a right to a lawyer and you have a right not to be tortured .
__de__ And what I recognized was that there was an incredible window of opportunity for us as a world community to come together and end torture as an investigative tool .
__de__ We often think of torture as being political torture or reserved for just the worst , but , in fact , 95 percent of torture today is not for political prisoners .
__de__ It is for people who are in broken-down legal systems , and unfortunately because torture is the cheapest form of investigation — it &apos;s cheaper than having a legal system , cheaper than having a lawyer and early access to counsel — it is what happens most of the time .
__de__ I believe today that it is possible for us as a world community , if we make a decision , to come together and end torture as an investigative tool in our lifetime , but it will require three things .
__de__ First is the training , empowerment , and connection of defenders worldwide .
__de__ The second is insuring that there is systematic early access to counsel .
