__de__ I &apos;m going to speak today about the relationship between science and human values .
__de__ Now , it &apos;s generally understood that questions of morality — questions of good and evil and right and wrong — are questions about which science officially has no opinion .
__de__ It &apos;s thought that science can help us get what we value , but it can never tell us what we ought to value .
__de__ And , consequently , most people — I think most people probably here — think that science will never answer the most important questions in human life : questions like , &quot; &quot; What is worth living for ? &quot; &quot; &quot; What is worth dying for ? &quot;
__de__ &quot; What constitutes a good life ? &quot;
__de__ So , I &apos;m going to argue that this is an illusion — that the separation between science and human values is an illusion — and actually quite a dangerous one at this point in human history .
__de__ Now , it &apos;s often said that science cannot give us a foundation for morality and human values , because science deals with facts , and facts and values seem to belong to different spheres .
__de__ It &apos;s often thought that there &apos;s no description of the way the world is that can tell us how the world ought to be .
__de__ But I think this is quite clearly untrue .
__de__ Values are a certain kind of fact .
__de__ They are facts about the well-being of conscious creatures .
__de__ Why is it that we don &apos;t have ethical obligations toward rocks ?
__de__ Why don &apos;t we feel compassion for rocks ?
__de__ It &apos;s because we don &apos;t think rocks can suffer . And if we &apos;re more concerned about our fellow primates than we are about insects , as indeed we are , it &apos;s because we think they &apos;re exposed to a greater range of potential happiness and suffering .
__de__ Now , the crucial thing to notice here is that this is a factual claim : This is something that we could be right or wrong about . And if we have misconstrued the relationship between biological complexity and the possibilities of experience well then we could be wrong about the inner lives of insects .
__de__ And there &apos;s no notion , no version of human morality and human values that I &apos;ve ever come across that is not at some point reducible to a concern about conscious experience and its possible changes .
__de__ Even if you get your values from religion , even if you think that good and evil ultimately relate to conditions after death — either to an eternity of happiness with God or an eternity of suffering in hell — you are still concerned about consciousness and its changes .
__de__ And to say that such changes can persist after death is itself a factual claim , which , of course , may or may not be true .
__de__ Now , to speak about the conditions of well-being in this life , for human beings , we know that there is a continuum of such facts .
__de__ We know that it &apos;s possible to live in a failed state , where everything that can go wrong does go wrong — where mothers cannot feed their children , where strangers cannot find the basis for peaceful collaboration , where people are murdered indiscriminately .
__de__ And we know that it &apos;s possible to move along this continuum towards something quite a bit more idyllic , to a place where a conference like this is even conceivable .
__de__ And we know — we know — that there are right and wrong answers to how to move in this space .
__de__ Would adding cholera to the water be a good idea ?
__de__ Probably not .
__de__ Would it be a good idea for everyone to believe in the evil eye , so that when bad things happened to them they immediately blame their neighbors ? Probably not .
__de__ There are truths to be known about how human communities flourish , whether or not we understand these truths .
__de__ And morality relates to these truths .
__de__ So , in talking about values we are talking about facts .
__de__ Now , of course our situation in the world can be understood at many levels — from the level of the genome on up to the level of economic systems and political arrangements .
__de__ But if we &apos;re going to talk about human well-being we are , of necessity , talking about the human brain .
__de__ Because we know that our experience of the world and of ourselves within it is realized in the brain — whatever happens after death .
__de__ Even if the suicide bomber does get 72 virgins in the afterlife , in this life , his personality — his rather unfortunate personality — is the product of his brain .
__de__ So the contributions of culture — if culture changes us , as indeed it does , it changes us by changing our brains .
__de__ And so therefore whatever cultural variation there is in how human beings flourish can , at least in principle , be understood in the context of a maturing science of the mind — neuroscience , psychology , etc .
__de__ So , what I &apos;m arguing is that value &apos;s reduced to facts — to facts about the conscious experience of conscious beings .
__de__ And we can therefore visualize a space of possible changes in the experience of these beings .
__de__ And I think of this as kind of a moral landscape , with peaks and valleys that correspond to differences in the well-being of conscious creatures , both personal and collective .
__de__ And one thing to notice is that perhaps there are states of human well-being that we rarely access , that few people access .
__de__ And these await our discovery .
__de__ Perhaps some of these states can be appropriately called mystical or spiritual .
__de__ Perhaps there are other states that we can &apos;t access because of how our minds are structured but other minds possibly could access them .
__de__ Now , let me be clear about what I &apos;m not saying . I &apos;m not saying that science is guaranteed to map this space , or that we will have scientific answers to every conceivable moral question .
