__nl__ When I was 11 , I remember waking up one morning to the sound of joy in my house .
__nl__ My father was listening to BBC News on his small , gray radio .
__nl__ There was a big smile on his face which was unusual then , because the news mostly depressed him .
__nl__ &quot; &quot; The Taliban are gone ! &quot; &quot; my father shouted .
__nl__ I didn &apos;t know what it meant , but I could see that my father was very , very happy .
__nl__ &quot; &quot; You can go to a real school now , &quot; &quot; he said .
__nl__ A morning that I will never forget .
__nl__ A real school .
__nl__ You see , I was six when the Taliban took over Afghanistan and made it illegal for girls to go to school .
__nl__ So for the next five years , I dressed as a boy to escort my older sister , who was no longer allowed to be outside alone , to a secret school .
__nl__ It was the only way we both could be educated .
__nl__ Each day , we took a different route so that no one would suspect where we were going .
__nl__ We would cover our books in grocery bags so it would seem we were just out shopping .
__nl__ The school was in a house , more than 100 of us packed in one small living room .
__nl__ It was cozy in winter but extremely hot in summer .
__nl__ We all knew we were risking our lives — the teacher , the students and our parents .
__nl__ From time to time , the school would suddenly be canceled for a week because Taliban were suspicious .
__nl__ We always wondered what they knew about us .
__nl__ Were we being followed ?
__nl__ Do they know where we live ?
__nl__ We were scared , but still , school was where we wanted to be .
__nl__ I was very lucky to grow up in a family where education was prized and daughters were treasured .
__nl__ My grandfather was an extraordinary man for his time .
__nl__ A total maverick from a remote province of Afghanistan , he insisted that his daughter , my mom , go to school , and for that he was disowned by his father .
__nl__ But my educated mother became a teacher .
__nl__ There she is .
__nl__ She retired two years ago , only to turn our house into a school for girls and women in our neighborhood .
__nl__ And my father — that &apos;s him — he was the first ever in his family to receive an education .
__nl__ There was no question that his children would receive an education , including his daughters , despite the Taliban , despite the risks .
__nl__ To him , there was greater risk in not educating his children .
__nl__ During Taliban years , I remember there were times I would get so frustrated by our life and always being scared and not seeing a future .
__nl__ I would want to quit , but my father , he would say , &quot; &quot; Listen , my daughter , you can lose everything you own in your life .
__nl__ Your money can be stolen . You can be forced to leave your home during a war .
__nl__ But the one thing that will always remain with you is what is here , and if we have to sell our blood to pay your school fees , we will .
__nl__ So do you still not want to continue ? &quot; &quot; Today I am 22 .
__nl__ I was raised in a country that has been destroyed by decades of war .
__nl__ Fewer than six percent of women my age have made it beyond high school , and had my family not been so committed to my education , I would be one of them .
__nl__ Instead , I stand here a proud graduate of Middlebury College .
__nl__ ( Applause ) When I returned to Afghanistan , my grandfather , the one exiled from his home for daring to educate his daughters , was among the first to congratulate me .
__nl__ He not only brags about my college degree , but also that I was the first woman , and that I am the first woman to drive him through the streets of Kabul .
__nl__ ( Applause ) My family believes in me .
__nl__ I dream big , but my family dreams even bigger for me .
__nl__ That &apos;s why I am a global ambassador for 10x10 , a global campaign to educate women .
__nl__ That &apos;s why I cofounded SOLA , the first and perhaps only boarding school for girls in Afghanistan , a country where it &apos;s still risky for girls to go to school .
__nl__ The exciting thing is that I see students at my school with ambition grabbing at opportunity .
__nl__ And I see their parents and their fathers who , like my own , advocate for them , despite and even in the face of daunting opposition .
__nl__ Like Ahmed . That &apos;s not his real name , and I cannot show you his face , but Ahmed is the father of one of my students .
