__nl__ In Oxford in the 1950s , there was a fantastic doctor , who was very unusual , named Alice Stewart .
__nl__ And Alice was unusual partly because , of course , she was a woman , which was pretty rare in the 1950s .
__nl__ And she was brilliant , she was one of the , at the time , the youngest Fellow to be elected to the Royal College of Physicians .
__nl__ She was unusual too because she continued to work after she got married , after she had kids , and even after she got divorced and was a single parent , she continued her medical work .
__nl__ And she was unusual because she was really interested in a new science , the emerging field of epidemiology , the study of patterns in disease .
__nl__ But like every scientist , she appreciated that to make her mark , what she needed to do was find a hard problem and solve it .
__nl__ The hard problem that Alice chose was the rising incidence of childhood cancers .
__nl__ Most disease is correlated with poverty , but in the case of childhood cancers , the children who were dying seemed mostly to come from affluent families .
__nl__ So , what , she wanted to know , could explain this anomaly ?
__nl__ Now , Alice had trouble getting funding for her research .
__nl__ In the end , she got just 1,000 pounds from the Lady Tata Memorial prize .
__nl__ And that meant she knew she only had one shot at collecting her data .
__nl__ Now , she had no idea what to look for .
__nl__ This really was a needle in a haystack sort of search , so she asked everything she could think of .
__nl__ Had the children eaten boiled sweets ?
__nl__ Had they consumed colored drinks ?
__nl__ Did they eat fish and chips ?
__nl__ Did they have indoor or outdoor plumbing ?
__nl__ What time of life had they started school ?
__nl__ And when her carbon copied questionnaire started to come back , one thing and one thing only jumped out with the statistical clarity of a kind that most scientists can only dream of .
__nl__ By a rate of two to one , the children who had died had had mothers who had been X-rayed when pregnant .
__nl__ Now that finding flew in the face of conventional wisdom .
__nl__ Conventional wisdom held that everything was safe up to a point , a threshold .
__nl__ It flew in the face of conventional wisdom , which was huge enthusiasm for the cool new technology of that age , which was the X-ray machine .
__nl__ And it flew in the face of doctors &apos; idea of themselves , which was as people who helped patients , they didn &apos;t harm them .
__nl__ Nevertheless , Alice Stewart rushed to publish her preliminary findings in The Lancet in 1956 .
__nl__ People got very excited , there was talk of the Nobel Prize , and Alice really was in a big hurry to try to study all the cases of childhood cancer she could find before they disappeared .
__nl__ In fact , she need not have hurried .
__nl__ It was fully 25 years before the British and medical — British and American medical establishments abandoned the practice of X-raying pregnant women .
__nl__ The data was out there , it was open , it was freely available , but nobody wanted to know .
__nl__ A child a week was dying , but nothing changed .
__nl__ Openness alone can &apos;t drive change .
__nl__ So for 25 years Alice Stewart had a very big fight on her hands .
__nl__ So , how did she know that she was right ?
__nl__ Well , she had a fantastic model for thinking .
__nl__ She worked with a statistician named George Kneale , and George was pretty much everything that Alice wasn &apos;t .
__nl__ So , Alice was very outgoing and sociable , and George was a recluse .
__nl__ Alice was very warm , very empathetic with her patients .
__nl__ George frankly preferred numbers to people .
__nl__ But he said this fantastic thing about their working relationship .
__nl__ He said , &quot; &quot; My job is to prove Dr. Stewart wrong . &quot; &quot; He actively sought disconfirmation .
__nl__ Different ways of looking at her models , at her statistics , different ways of crunching the data in order to disprove her .
__nl__ He saw his job as creating conflict around her theories .
__nl__ Because it was only by not being able to prove that she was wrong , that George could give Alice the confidence she needed to know that she was right .
__nl__ It &apos;s a fantastic model of collaboration — thinking partners who aren &apos;t echo chambers .
__nl__ I wonder how many of us have , or dare to have , such collaborators .
__nl__ Alice and George were very good at conflict .
__nl__ They saw it as thinking .
__nl__ So what does that kind of constructive conflict require ?
__nl__ Well , first of all , it requires that we find people who are very different from ourselves .
__nl__ That means we have to resist the neurobiological drive , which means that we really prefer people mostly like ourselves , and it means we have to seek out people with different backgrounds , different disciplines , different ways of thinking and different experience , and find ways to engage with them .
__nl__ That requires a lot of patience and a lot of energy .
__nl__ And the more I &apos;ve thought about this , the more I think , really , that that &apos;s a kind of love .
__nl__ Because you simply won &apos;t commit that kind of energy and time if you don &apos;t really care .
__nl__ And it also means that we have to be prepared to change our minds .
__nl__ Alice &apos;s daughter told me that every time Alice went head-to-head with a fellow scientist , they made her think and think and think again .
